@0    = ~Speak for yourself.~
@1    = ~Actually, I do. Well, for me, and for my *friend*.~
@2    = ~Ah, how sweet. I like how you emphasized 'friend'. Between us girls, rookie men do not appreciate fellow rookie women in bed.~
@3    = ~Hey, why-~
@4    = ~No reason. It just accidentally came to me while I was watching that drool gather in the corner of your mouth.~
@5    = ~(Blows out a huge bubble of saliva.)~
@6    = ~Yes, that drool... Feh.~
@7    = ~I can see that my immaturity offends Your Grace, so maybe Your Grace can take her experienced bottom elsewhere? Unless she's interested in a certain greenhorn more than she cares to admit?~
@8    = ~Nonsense. Play on, kids.~
@9    = ~Ouf. It's great to have someone like you around! Someone not overly proficient, if you know what I mean.~
@10   = ~I urge you to think again. Due to this unfortunate synergy we are likely to die together quite soon.~
@11   = ~It seems we have something in common.~
@12   = ~I know! It's so exciting!~
@13   = ~Novices or veterans - we're all here to work together towards a common goal.~
@14   = ~Peony, you're the last person I want to talk to right now. ~
@15   = ~You only be talking to him that way because he be a half-orc, and so cannot be honorable and valorous. I be knowing that it be untrue.~
@16   = ~How peculiar. I had a similar rush of emotions when I saw you.~
@17   = ~Really? You thought I was a pirate?~
@18   = ~I actually meant... him.~
@19   = ~Hey, that's just *weird*! Besides, I saw him first!~
@20   = ~...a newly appointed meat shield on the brink of glorious corpsehood...~
@21   = ~I trust I'm not grisly?~
@22   = ~Wow! So, you meet me, and...?~
@23   = ~Your words are most pleasant, my lady.~
@24   = ~(Clear your throat and spit under her feet.) Now lass, didn't I tell you how I was thrown overboard and ripped a shark's throat out with my own fingernails?~
@25   = ~Peony, I think you are unbalancing his inner peace.~
@26   = ~Inner peace? Who needs it!~
@27   = ~Everyone.~
@28   = ~Pirates don't!~
@29   = ~You will reduce our already slim chances of survival by making allegations that could potentially set the authorities against us. (Sigh.) ~
@30   = ~That's me! A dashing pirate! Rrgh!~
@31   = ~Damn, and I hoped it was all covered up. Well, I guess father *was* the last one to know.~
@32   = ~Peony, I'm sorry to disappoint you, but I'm not a pirate.~
@33   = ~My lady, you're mistaken. I'm not a buccaneer, but indeed the eldest son and heir of Ser Roedrik the Fierce.~
@34   = ~I'm NOT A BLOODY PIRATE, you stupid cow!!!~
@35   = ~Tacky? I'd say revolting. Incredibly bad taste.~
@36   = ~Don't mind her, it's sweet!~
@37   = ~I shall strive then to compliment you in a non-tacky way, my lady.~
@38   = ~I'm glad that my meager words put a smil- er... a grin on your face. ~
@39   = ~I should have foreseen that a scolding would come along with praise. For nothing sweet in our sorrowful world comes without more than a shade of bitterness. ~
@40   = ~I thought you might like it! And you did! Woo-hoo!~
@41   = ~I hope that gets me off the hook for today.~
@42   = ~Yes, and all of them horrid.~
@43   = ~For something? That be the best and most noble origin one can have.~
@44   = ~Peony, I don't think you understood his meaning.~
@45   = ~Oh? And you did, right?~
@46   = ~I think I can relate to his experiences. The past lives that cloud my present self, my coming to the temple from my parent's home and the journey I am undertaking, enable me to feel very close to him.~
@47   = ~Prachi, nobody else here thinks like you in millennia and past lives. One day at a time is good enough for us!~
@48   = ~It's a wise piece of advice. Besides, you have a wonderful smile.~
@49   = ~Yeah, he does at that! Funny you noticed it.~
@50   = ~You wish.~
@51   = ~On the contrary, it was the most intelligent thing he's said in a while. Why, it was almost lordly.~
@52   = ~You're both so mean!~
@53   = ~We do not choose our roles, and it spells doom to wish for a particular destiny.~
@54   = ~Tee-hee! Not in my books!~
@55   = ~That does be a strange puzzle. I be sure that everyone does be needing a good commander, but the evil bosses- Aha, I know! I good commander, like Sir Nord or him be a good thing, and the evil bosses be doomed!~
@56   = ~Yes, Hildury is right, it's *different*!~
@57   = ~Anarchy is not good for anyone. ~
@58   = ~Thank you, Hildury. I know what I know - me being in charge is the right thing. ~
@59   = ~All right, you are correct, but here and now I'm the one giving orders and nothing is going to change that! ~
@60   = ~And the evil bosses got a bellyful of me. How neat is that?~
@61   = ~You seem to be a perfect match.~
@62   = ~You think so? Then why the sour face?~
@63   = ~Peony, I think you wanted to know if he considered you a sidekick. I don't think so.~
@64   = ~He'd better not!~
@65   = ~You're not a sidekick! Cross my heart! ~
@66   = ~I think we both are supernumerary here, Peony, and our mighty foes are about to shorten the dramatis personae. They wouldn't care who's a sidekick to whom, so why should we?~
@67   = ~I didn't mean it at all, my lady. I feel that you have an enormously important role to play in this drama.~
@68   = ~What would you like to be? ~
@69   = ~Your desires are irrelevant, gnome. You'll be what I let you be.~
@70   = ~Yes, did you ever do such a thing?~
@71   = ~Wow, can you shout that a bit louder? I am sure that some curious orcs a few miles away are having difficulty picking up the details of my private life. ~
@72   = ~Yep! I am a man grown, you know. ~
@73   = ~And why would you be interested in that, Peony? ~
@74   = ~Life is too short to spend it on momentary pleasures. ~
@75   = ~Indeed, for one must hurry to sample life's pleasures before death cuts him down in his prime. ~
@76   = ~No, I have not, my lady. ~
@77   = ~This is something I did not expect. Are you sure?~
@78   = ~Yes, and you didn't expect it? Well, you are a fool then.~
@79   = ~It was you who helped me understand it. ~
@80   = ~Jaemal, I sense that it is an important revelation for you, but I want it to be clear that I have no interest in you. ~
@81   = ~Psst. (No, I just said it to get rid of the girl without offending her.)~
@82   = ~You'll be in trouble if you court someone else, though.~
@83   = ~Thank you for being frank.~
@84   = ~It's a strange land with more than one mystery.~
@85   = ~I suppose I am, at that.~
@86   = ~Pretty. It does always come down to pretty. But why she be pretty? She be small and blue-haired, like a doll children play with. (Sigh) And I did be thinking understanding my own kinsman would be easier than humans and elves and dwarves.~
@87   = ~Because he's not properly wed. It is a man's duty as much as a woman's to enter a marriage that is appointed by the stars when the time is right.~
@88   = ~Stars? Hades, I won't let some twinkling thingies pick *my* husband, thank you very much! They can't even see him properly from up there!~
@89   = ~The stars and gods know all.~
@90   = ~Well, I'm not as good as you're at conversing with stars, so I'll just chat with the mortal man right in front of me. So, why haven't you kissed a girl or two yet? The marriage thing?~
@91   = ~I'm waiting for my true love.~
@92   = ~Who knows? It just... didn't happen.~
@93   = ~Because I am not attracted to women, Peony.~
@94   = ~You have a very long nose, Peony. Even for a gnome.~
@95   = ~He-he, it wasn't for the lack of trying, I can tell you that!~
@96   = ~Because I always *was kissed* before I kissed them myself. ~
@97   = ~I lied. Of course I've kissed a comely maiden or two. I'm a man grown. ~
@98   = ~Because you desperately tried to decorate your rather primitive persona. It's in the same league as your pathetic hair.~
@99   = ~As if you don't dye yours!~
@100  = ~Please. Lies are only good when they are not blatantly obvious. Same goes for illusions, of course.~
@101  = ~Argh! She drives me crazy, that... that vixen! Talk to me, will you? Do you want to know about this illusionist thing? Why I became one?~
@102  = ~Because you're a gnome?~
@103  = ~Nope, but you can tell me any time, even now. ~
@104  = ~I don't know your reasons, but I approve of your choice. You might as well occupy yourself with illusions that are real, rather than reality that is illusory. ~
@105  = ~Accidentally?~
@106  = ~My lady, I prefer you telling me to guessing.~
@107  = ~Nah, Peony, I am sorry, but I think Salomeya is right. You're simply not interesting enough... at least compared to her.~
@108  = ~See, little liar? Truth can be very, very useful.~
@109  = ~Hussy!~
@110  = ~Where did you pick up such a horrible word, Fluffy? Now, don't make a scene.  Learn to lose graciously. It's half of future victory.~
@111  = ~For a moment I did be thinking that it be beautiful. But then I thought that a man can only be won by the deeds of valor.~
@112  = ~Oh, you get it all backwards! Deeds of valor are for men to win our hearts with!~
@113  = ~Nay, Peony, where honor dies, defeat lies. For women as well as men.~
@114  = ~So, how does one go about love honest-like? Grab a man by his shirt and pull him into the bushes?~
@115  = ~If you be stronger and a she-orc on the raid...~
@116  = ~You did *that*?!~
@117  = ~I did many dishonorable things before my revelation. That be why I will not be doing anything dishonorable again.~
@118  = ~Bah, think what you want. It's *my* dream, and there's nothing wrong with it. Right, my pirate?~
@119  = ~Er... impressive.~
@120  = ~I suppose I must be glad that we're in a close proximity to the end of the world and are already moving in the right direction. Just in case you transcend and create that perfect illusion.~
@121  = ~I guess there's a difference between Salomeya and you after all. For a moment I thought you were exactly the same!~
@122  = ~Yes, it is very beautiful. Only, why do you need to involve all those other men? ~
@123  = ~That sounds like one big lie to me. ~
@124  = ~Killing men in the name of vanity is not right.~
@125  = ~Yep, and killing them in the name of duty is so much better! Besides, who said they'd be dead at all? They'll lie there by the curb for a bit, then gather their senses and go back home.~
@126  = ~That's... that's better.~
@127  = ~Glad you approve.~
@128  = ~Why did not you try enchantment spells then, Peony?~
@129  = ~There is something disturbing about that image. ~
@130  = ~And how do I fit into this picture of seducing mankind? ~
@131  = ~The only part that has any degree of realism to it is the one with men falling down from exhaustion. ~
@132  = ~This is about as fascinating as watching a slug make its progress across the palace's dungeons instead of enjoying the banquet upstairs.~
@133  = ~Before we die and all that, I want to tell you that I love you one more time!~
@134  = ~What, the previous three thousand and eleven were not enough?~
@135  = ~You scolded me for being a pessimist all this time, and now you're suddenly agreeing with me. Now I'm scared.~
@136  = ~My lady, if we should fall, I will die with your name on my lips.~
@137  = ~I love you too! ~
@138  = ~Nothing.~
@139  = ~No, you don't. And we don't even *have* to be here. I just don't get it why it's such a big deal if the stupid demons get what they want. They're slavers, and all, but... ah, doesn't matter. We're here now. Let's go and not die.~
@140  = ~This is no stupid tree! Well, it *is* but it's different.~
@141  = ~Stupid demons. I just don't get why it's such a big deal if they get what they want. They're slavers, and all, but... ah, doesn't matter. We're here now. Let's go and not die.~
@142  = ~(Shivers) Thanks, that was really soothing!~
@143  = ~That's just stupid! Why do we have to die in the first place because of two stupid demons?! I just don't get why it's such a big deal if they get what they want. They're slavers, and all, but... ah, doesn't matter. We're here now. Let's go and not die.~
@144  = ~You promise anyways, all right? And I will try to be strong. We... we can tough it out together.~
@145  = ~I... I will try to be strong then. Someone ought to. You try too, all right? We'll tough it out together.~
@146  = ~That's exactly what I keep telling myself. Only it doesn't help much.~
@147  = ~Oh, you found the worst possible time to get back at me!~
@148  = ~'And now let's move on.' I hate it when you act like a general with me.~
@149  = ~I have to, Peony. ~
@150  = ~What do you want from me? ~
@151  = ~I could promise you to be careful, but it would sound strange under the circumstances.~
@152  = ~Let me do my job. There is a price to be paid for overthrowing Isair and Madae, and it could well be our lives. I am trying to make sure that the losses are minimal.~
@153  = ~Oi, I'll have to live a long-long life. I'll give it my very best shot!~
@154  = ~It must be this place. At first I thought that it was pretty, but it sort of weighs you down. It's as if it has eyes everywhere, and they are all unfriendly.~
@155  = ~Ghosts tend to be that way.~
@156  = ~Yes, my lady, I know what you mean. But I am certain that after we overthrow Isair and Madae the evil enchantment will be gone from the Severed Hand. ~
@157  = ~Just try not to think about it. You know, it's the same way when you climb a tall tree.  You don't look down, and then it's all right. But if you do...~
@158  = ~Whatever.~
@159  = ~Heh, at least if we die, we'll die happy.~
@160  = ~(She makes her best effort to smile.) I'll change my name to Gurgle just in case.~
@161  = ~I... I'd rather you didn't die, sweetie.~
@162  = ~I'd rather nobody died, my dear. But there is a price to be paid for overthrowing Isair and Madae, and it could well be our lives.~
@163  = ~We won't. We're far too nice to perish. ~
@164  = ~You are scared?! I'm terrified!!!~
@165  = ~Why? There is always resurrection, no?~
@166  = ~Peony, I love you too. And we're not going to die. At least not now. ~
@167  = ~Don't do that, please. For so long you remained the only person who gave me hope. Don't take it away. I can't bear it-~
@168  = ~Well, let it be three thousand and twelve, all right?~
@169  = ~All right. I love you too.~
@170  = ~Peony, are you... frightened?~
@171  = ~No, I will not have you stop at that. You're going to say it to me at least three *hundred* thousand more times.~
@172  = ~All right.~
@173  = ~I was thinking-~
@174  = ~Again?!~
@175  = ~Yes, my lady?~
@176  = ~You sharing your thoughts is a bright light that breaks through the gloomy shadows of disaster that ever loom around us.~
@177  = ~So, go on!~
@178  = ~All right. (She does not quite succeed in presenting you with a meek look. You get the feeling that you're going to be nagged until you agree to her proposition.)~
@179  = ~Well, the danger is that we can get stuck there for a year or two, but hells, it's worth the risk!~
@180  = ~(Peony kisses you excitedly on both cheeks.) Ah, I'll have to get a dress with ruffles and a hat with a scarf. They always look so wonderful in the breeze! ~
@181  = ~Oh, you're going get that too, and a lot of it. If my family is anything, it's informal and friendly! But you'll not avoid the pomp, sweetie. You're going to be a battle-celebrant once we destroy Isair and Madae.~
@182  = ~I suppose. You've never asked me for anything before, so I feel that we should do it. I will speak with Oswald and will arrange everything to your satisfaction. ~
@183  = ~Peony, please. I'll not turn into a jolly idiot overnight.~
@184  = ~I'll think on that, all right?~
@185  = ~But you have to get used to it, sweetie. You're going to be a battle-celebrant once we destroy Isair and Madae.~
@186  = ~You know what? You're hopeless.~
@187  = ~Really?! But that's awesome!~
@188  = ~I know. You're hopeless.~
@189  = ~A dead man's - nothing. Yours - everything.~
@190  = ~You've never asked me for anything before, so I feel that we should do it, if we survive. I will speak with Oswald and will arrange everything to your satisfaction. ~
@191  = ~Assuming that destiny is kinder than usual, and we overcome our mighty foes, well, if I have to be paraded before your relatives it might as well be done in style. You'll have your wish, if Oswald is amenable.~
@192  = ~I don't understand. Do you truly want to go straight home after we're done here? I thought that with your unseemly optimism you wanted to adventure for a few more years.~
@193  = ~You're wonderful, absolutely wonderful! (Peony kisses you excitedly on both cheeks.) Ah, I'll have to get a dress with ruffles and a hat with a scarf. They always look so wonderful in the breeze! ~
@194  = ~Uhm, yes, I did. That's going to ruin this plan, right. Unless Oswald will still remember us twenty years down the road. ~
@195  = ~Ouf, thank the gods!~
@196  = ~I guess if I have to be paraded before your relatives, it might as well be done in style. You'll have your wish, if Oswald is amenable to the pleasure cruise.~
@197  = ~Why don't you amend your plan a bit? We stop by Silverymoon, and then continue on from there.~
@198  = ~'Paraded'? And I was sooooo proud of you! Well, until you said that. All right, forget it.~
@199  = ~Peony, that was an unfortunate choice of words is all. I am proud to have you on my arm!~
@200  = ~Ouf, thanks the gods!~
@201  = ~I am not much of a man for ceremonies, my love. An airship landing in Silverymoon is bound to attract eyes, and I dread the feeling of being the center of everyone's attention. ~
@202  = ~I'd rather meet your folks in a private, informal and hopefully friendly way.~
@203  = ~Told you! (Sigh.) Pretty too.~
@204  = ~Peony, please. I'll not change my mind.~
@205  = ~You've never asked me for anything before, so I feel that we should do it anyway. Silly or not. I will speak with Oswald and will arrange everything to your satisfaction. ~
@206  = ~I guess if I have to be paraded before your relatives it might as well be done in style. You'll have your wish, if Oswald is amenable to the pleasure cruises.~
@207  = ~Do you want to go straight home after we're done here? I thought you wanted to adventure for a few more years.~
@208  = ~My dear, your sighs are misdirected. I can promise you this very thing you want, but how much is a dead man's promise worth to you? ~
@209  = ~ Let's talk Oswald into driving the ship to Silverymoon! My grandma would fall off her chair when she sees you! And the ship.~
@210  = ~You were right. It is silly.~
@211  = ~I guess if I have to be paraded before your relatives it might as well be done in style!~
@212  = ~My lady, say no more! I will speak with Oswald and will arrange everything to your satisfaction. ~
@213  = ~My dear, I can promise you that, but how much is a dead man's promise worth to you? ~
@214  = ~Tee-hee! It's itsy-bitsy silly.~
@215  = ~Oi. Well, I hope so. It's a bit silly.~
@216  = ~I sure hoped you'd like it. It's a bit silly.~
@217  = ~Yeah, and you, again, weren't.~
@218  = ~Oh, <CHARNAME>, <CHARNAME>, there's one thing I forgot to ask you! How many babies would you like to have?~
@219  = ~Wh-what?!~
@220  = ~I don't rightly know, my sweet bride. I will welcome however many the gods send us.~
@221  = ~I don't rightly know, my lady. I will welcome however many the gods send us.~
@222  = ~(Gasp) Peony, we didn't even do it yet, and you're already thinking about babies!~
@223  = ~Peony, I haven't given it a thought yet. I'm too young for this to be relevant in my life.~
@224  = ~One?~
@225  = ~That's easy: None.~
@226  = ~I want a large family with a whole bunch of kids!~
@227  = ~Oi! I've just have a revelation. You see, if I am to become a Chosen of Mystra.... Well, they all are so different! I can't be *just* like Lady Alustriel. Of course, I'm already not like her, seeing as I am a Gnome, but still. I can't have the same hair and the same number of babies. And I really like the hair!~
@228  = ~Heh, I'll think about it later. It's waaaay too complicated.~
@229  = ~Yep!~
@230  = ~(Touches her hair.) Don't you see that the similarities run far deeper than that?! I have all talents necessary to become an immortal Chosen of Mystra!~
@231  = ~I'm not saying that you don't have what it takes-~
@232  = ~Well, once you've become one we can talk about it again. ~
@233  = ~Then you can always find someone else to father all these sons? Right? ~
@234  = ~I suppose we can do nothing then but to have a dozen children and all of them boys. (Sigh.)~
@235  = ~So? We're better! You're a perfectly wonderful Gnome, and I have all talents necessary to become an immortal Chosen of Mystra!~
@236  = ~I suppose we can do nothing then but to have a dozen children and all of them boys. (Sigh.) ~
@237  = ~Oh. Well, that could be a problem.~
@238  = ~I have all talents necessary to become an immortal Chosen of Mystra!~
@239  = ~You're not an Elf, true, but I have all talents necessary to become an immortal Chosen of Mystra!~
@240  = ~It's just... you see, Lady Alustriel has twelve sons!~
@241  = ~Lady Alustriel is an immortal Chosen of Mystra, and her husband was a long-living elven lord.~
@242  = ~Lady Alustriel is an immortal Chosen of Mystra, and her husband was... er... an elf. But you are not immortal, my sweet girl.~
@243  = ~Peony, you are a Gnome, and I am not. I don't know if we even can have children together. ~
@244  = ~Well, we're only Gnomes, Peony, and not some great immortal humans or elves. ~
@245  = ~I understand your fascination with the Lady Alustriel, Peony, but wouldn't copying her hairstyle be sufficient? ~
@246  = ~That sounds quite lovely. I don't know if we would be able to get there, but we can always try.~
@247  = ~Really? Just like Lady Alustriel? She has twelve sons!~
@248  = ~Well, we're only Gnomes, Peony, and not some great immortal humans or elves, so we might not get twelve, but- ~
@249  = ~Lady Alustriel has twelve sons!~
@250  = ~And? It's fun! Well, not as much fun as making them, but I wouldn't know that with you, would I?~
@251  = ~Oh. You sound so right. As usual.~
@252  = ~And you sound disappointed. Would you rather I had a specific number in mind?~
@253  = ~Yes, I am always right, dear.~
@254  = ~We'll start with one, and then we'll see. How's that for an answer? ~
@255  = ~So, what do you think about it?~
@256  = ~Are you all right? You look sickened... Aha, I know! Nope, I'm not pregnant, silly. It's a theoretical question.~
@257  = ~ You're the most wonderful man I know!~
@258  = ~Really?~
@259  = ~I take it you're not angry anymore for not taking you in a manly fashion the other night? ~
@260  = ~I take it you're not angry anymore for my lack of patience the other night?~
@261  = ~My lady, I am very flattered by this assessment.~
@262  = ~My lady, this is exactly how a man wants his wife to think of him, and I am very grateful that you do.~
@263  = ~Sadly, you are probably among the last people to ever know me.~
@264  = ~Peony, your perpetual cheerfulness gives me a headache. I just can't take it right now.~
@265  = ~How so? The Legion of Chimera is an evil-evil-evil thing as opposite to the evil-evil thing it was a day before yesterday? Nah, if we were in Thay then politics would have been fun with all the zulkirs. Here, even the *weather* holds more surprises. After all we might *not* get a snowstorm.~
@266  = ~Of course you listen. You're just saying this to offend me. And that's just mean!~
@267  = ~Nah, I like it the way it is. Hey, doesn't this little ring look just phantasmagoric?~
@268  = ~He-he, I appreciate your faith in me! Hey, maybe it's not as bad as I imagined? Come, come. Oh. Doesn't this little ring look just phantasmagoric?~
@269  = ~I am trying to avert this disaster, believe me! Sometimes I want to talk to you, and nothing comes to my mind. So I kiss you instead, and then one thing leads to another... well, you know.~
@270  = ~Don't worry about that, Peony, please. We will have our talkative days, and our quiet days, like every other couple.~
@271  = ~*Nothing* comes to your mind? Peony, I don't believe that.~
@272  = ~My dear lady. nothing has changed between us just because we fell in love. I will be delighted to talk about anything with you.~
@273  = ~Which is good, because I begrudge time for words. We do not have much left, and there are more important things to accomplish before our mighty adversaries kill us. ~
@274  = ~We can always discuss the current political situation, seeing as it changes more than the weather.~
@275  = ~That sounds kind of nice, but way too creepy. I just want to talk, but nothing comes to my mind. So I kiss you instead, and then one thing leads to another... well, you know.~
@276  = ~My dear lady, nothing has changed between us just because we fell in love. I will be delighted to talk about anything with you.~
@277  = ~That you can do on your own! In *silence*.~
@278  = ~And that involves talking! When people don't have anything to tell to one another, it's *bad*!~
@279  = ~We can always discuss the current political situation, seeing it as changes more than the weather.~
@280  = ~That doesn't sound too bad, especially coming from you!~
@281  = ~And you're talking a special kind of nonsense. When people don't have anything to tell to one another, it's *bad*!~
@282  = ~See, I find we don't talk much any more.~
@283  = ~Yes, it's a blessing.~
@284  = ~Why's that?~
@285  = ~I begrudge time for words. We do not have much left, and there are more important things to accomplish before our mighty adversaries kill us. ~
@286  = ~My lady, you know that I am always happy to listen to whatever you have to say. ~
@287  = ~Peony, there is a special kind of silence to which words simply can't compare to. ~
@288  = ~Maybe that's just it. You so completely *accept* me that I can blurt out anything, and you'll still smile and listen. Hmm...~
@289  = ~So, what would you propose we do about it?~
