@539  = ~Nope! And my conjuration phase came in handy when I summoned all those free laborers to rebuild it!~
@540  = ~It's not like one should give up on everything though. That would be just silly.~
@541  = ~Why, thank you! (Blushes so hard that she does remind you of a peony for a moment.)~
@542  = ~I was a little gnomling back then, and only read the book because grandma kept it locked away. Of course afterwards I went through my transmuter phase, my evocation and invocation phase-~
@543  = ~And your house survived you playing with fireballs?~
@544  = ~(Nod along)~
@545  = ~I think I understand. You tried it all, but your first love - illusionism- was the most interesting.~
@546  = ~Sounds like you had an exciting life. ~
@547  = ~Alright, I'm telling! I read it in one book that love is an illusion, and beauty is an illusion. So I decided if I'm an illusionist, I'll be a mistress of it all!~
@548  = ~You wanted to be a mistress of love and beauty?! Wow. ~
@549  = ~Uhm?~
@550  = ~An interesting reason, my lady. I must say that you've succeeded in achieving your goal.~
@551  = ~Mustering against fate and overwhelming odds is impossible, Peony. You'll achieve nothing but the better understanding of the universal futility of all efforts.~
@552  = ~But it takes all the fun out of it!~
@553  = ~Accidental?! Nothing I do is accidental! Erm... that's not exactly the truth, but it sure sounded nice.~
@554  = ~Huh? It's that bad, isn't it? You poor soul. I feel almost compelled to tell you, not leave you hanging like that.~
@555  = ~Will I tell you? Or won't I? Tee-hee, the suspense is *killing* me.~
@556  = ~It's killing *you*?! Well, think of what it does to me!~
@557  = ~If you don't want to tell, then don't. ~
@558  = ~Peony, please, please, please.... Pretty please? ~
@559  = ~I'll wager my favorite cloak against the last year's snows that the cruel weapons of our foes will get there faster than the suspense. ~
@560  = ~My lady, the choice is yours. ~
@561  = ~That's so stupid! Yes, I'm a gnome, and I'm an illusionist, but I'm not an illusionist because I'm a gnome, Mister. Oh, no. I could have as easily became a necromancer. If I *wanted* to.~
@562  = ~All right, all right, I'm sorry. Why did you *want* to become an illusionist? ~
@563  = ~I might have erred in guessing at your reasons, but I approve of your choice. You might as well occupy yourself with illusions that are real, rather than reality that is illusory. ~
@564  = ~So it was not er... because of a tradition, and it was not accidental that you became an illusionist.~
@565  = ~My lady, if I gave offence, I apologize. I should have asked you to tell me instead of guessing.~
@566  = ~<CHARNAME>, <CHARNAME>! Have you ever kissed a girl?~
@567  = ~ Wow, can you shout that a bit louder? I am sure that some curious orcs a few miles away are having difficulty picking up the details of my private life. ~
@568  = ~Life is too short to spend it on the momentary pleasures. ~
@569  = ~Indeed, for one must hurry to sample life's pleasures afore the death cuts him down in his prime. ~
@570  = ~So you think I will marry some fool?! Pfft. Hmm... unless he's funny....~
@571  = ~Well, thank you.~
@572  = ~Maybe we shall, and maybe we shan't. Tee-hee! I don't want you to think me easy!~
@573  = ~Not attracted to wome- Oh. That's a damnable pity, I tell you!~
@574  = ~You know, it doesn't matter much. I kissed hundreds of boys... well, not hundreds, of course, but at least nine... or twelve? Well, thirteen if cousins twice-removed count. Such an unlucky number.~
@575  = ~But it never really worked out. (Sigh.) I'll end up a spinster.~
@576  = ~You are young and will yet find the man of your dreams. Only it won't be me.~
@577  = ~No you won't! ~
@578  = ~It is indeed likely; seeing the scores of powerful opponents that are working towards ending our lives. ~
@579  = ~My lady, you are lovelier than all the spring blossoms. You will be wed before you know it to the luckiest man in the world. ~
@580  = ~Shall we increase the tally to the less unfortunate fourteen? ~
@581  = ~You're just trying to infect me with your melancholy, aren't you? Then we can wipe each other's tears, the way some people have a laugh together. Hmm... I think, I'd rather laugh alone than cry.~
@582  = ~Because I'm an enchantress? Er... not *technically* but in essence?~
@583  = ~Because you're an enchantress.~
@584  = ~And because you're pretty. And smart. And funny.~
@585  = ~Something like that, yes.~
@586  = ~No, because men are fools.~
@587  = ~Thank you very much. And I think I'd have known the man of my dreams the moment I saw him.~
@588  = ~Oh. Well. I wish you many gems and children.~
@589  = ~And let them stay in the past. They lie about old flames rekindled. They never burn as bright as the new ones. (Giggle.) I kissed hundreds of boys... well, not hundreds, of course, but at least nine... or twelve? Well, thirteen if cousins twice-removed count. Such an unlucky number.~
@590  = ~But it never really worked out, you know? (Sigh.) I'll end up a spinster.~
@591  = ~No you won't!~
@592  = ~It is indeed likely; seeing the scores of powerful opponents that are working towards ending our lives.~
@593  = ~Shall we increase the tally to the less unfortunate fourteen?~
@594  = ~That's her loss! I kissed hundreds of boys... well, not hundreds, of course, but at least nine... or twelve? Well, thirteen if cousins twice-removed count. Such an unlucky number.~
@595  = ~It is indeed likely; seeing that scores of powerful opponents are working towards ending our lives. ~
@596  = ~No? Why's that?~
@597  = ~He-he, it wasn't for the lack of trying, I tell you that!~
@598  = ~I lied. Of course I kissed a comely maiden or two. I'm a man grown. ~
@599  = ~No reason. Tee-hee! I kissed hundreds of boys... well, not hundreds, of course, but at least... nine or twelve? Well, thirteen if cousins twice-removed count. Such an unlucky number.~
@600  = ~Oh. So you have a sweetie already?~
@601  = ~Yes, but she is far away, unlike, say, you. ~
@602  = ~No, those affairs all belong to the past.~
@603  = ~Yes. ~
@604  = ~Nah-nah-nah! That's *you* who needs to yell the answer! So that the poor dears can hear out all the details!~
@605  = ~YES! I KISSED GIRLS WHILE YOU WERE STILL PLAYING WITH DOLLS!~
@606  = ~NO, I HAVEN'T YET KISSED A GIRL!~
@607  = ~I understand the orcs.  They have been freezing out there with nothing much to do for weeks, but why would you be interested in that, Peony? ~
@608  = ~I prefer to leave the orcs hanging for more. No, Peony... (you switch to the dramatic whisper.) I haven't kissed anyone but my sisters, and them in a brotherly way before you start thinking something untoward. Life is too short to spend it on momentary pleasures. ~
@609  = ~Indeed, Peony, I have loved and kissed womenfolk, for one must hurry to sample life's pleasures afore  death cuts him down in his prime. ~
@610  = ~You're some kind of a prodigy, aren't you?~
@611  = ~Whatever! It's boring. Let's have some fun instead! Guess who I always wanted to be if I couldn't be the hero? A love interest, that's who. Yep, they are always grand ladies, like Lady Alustriel.~
@612  = ~But that would make us sweeties. Oops!~
@613  = ~Because we'll shred them into chips, set a fire to them and then throw the ashes to the wind! We're the ones writing this play, silly, not them. And that they are powerful is good, because we'll only look so much more heroic.~
@614  = ~So, stop sulking and you'd better guess who I always wanted to be if I couldn't be the hero? A love interest, that's who. Yep, they are always grand ladies, like Lady Alustriel.~
@615  = ~Woo-hoo! You're great! You know what I always wanted to be if I weren't the hero? A love interest. Yep, they are always grand ladies, like Lady Alustriel.~
@616  = ~Well, if you want to prove something to me, I guess, you don't consider me a sidekick material. And you'd better not, because I won't stand for that, Mister!~
@617  = ~I didn't mean that at all, lady. I feel that you have an enormously important role to play in this drama.~
@618  = ~Your desires are irrelevant, gnome. You'll be what I'd let you to be.~
@619  = ~Oh, that's just stupid. Of course not! People can do things on their own, you know, without some guy yelling orders at them all the time. In fact, the world would have been a better place without the bosses. Hey, I am sure you had a bellyful of these evil bosses by now. Or am I wrong?~
@620  = ~Yes, but it's *different*!~
@621  = ~I know what I know - me being in charge is the right thing. ~
@622  = ~Well, magnificent - maybe, but phantasmagoric.... Nope, not yet! You'll have to work harder to be that! And don't put your nose too high up in the air. I almost heard you calling me a sidekick. I won't stand for that, Mister!~
@623  = ~I can be very, very understanding, and I am beautiful.... Oh, but hey! Does that mean that you consider me sidekick material? I won't stand for that, Mister!~
@624  = ~I didn't mean that at all, my lady. I feel that you have an enormously important role to play in this drama.~
@625  = ~That was just so... uncute! And stupid. Pfft.~
@626  = ~Small fry? Is that what we all are to you? Even me? I won't stand for being your sidekick, Mister!~
@627  = ~Our mighty foes are about to shorten the dramatis personae. They don't care who's a sidekick to whom, so why should we?~
@628  = ~If someone has to be in charge, I suppose you aren't half bad. At the very least you are ever so polite.~
@629  = ~Oh, Peony, I'm so tired of the responsibility. I wish there was someone who understood my burdens, a kindly, beautiful maiden, perhaps....~
@630  = ~Aren't half bad? I'm magnificent, incredible and phantasmagoric! ~
@631  = ~*If* somebody has to be in charge? Somebody always has to be in charge, Peony.~
@632  = ~I see that you do not hold me in high esteem, my lady, but I shall prove my worth to you, to my father, to Sir Nord, to Lord Ulbrec and to the rest of the North if need be.~
@633  = ~Your condescendence does not hit the mark, stupid girl. I know that I am a great man, and giggling behind my back won't change it.~
@634  = ~Yep! Oh, but hey! Does that mean that you consider me sidekick material? I won't stand for that, Mister!~
@635  = ~I think we both are supernumerary here, Peony, and our mighty foes are about to shorten the dramatis personae. They don't care who's a sidekick to whom, so why should we?~
@636  = ~I didn't mean it at all, lady. I feel that you have an enormously important role to play in this drama.~
@637  = ~If someone has to be in charge, I suppose you aren't half that bad.~
@638  = ~Oh, Peony, I'm so tired of the responsibility. I wish there was someone who understood my burdens, a kindly beautiful maiden, perhaps....~
@639  = ~I guess.... So long as you don't let your head grow too big, daydreaming about what he might have thought, it's all right.~
@640  = ~I won't, I promise.~
@641  = ~Ah, but you'll always be here to knock me down a peg!~
@642  = ~I'm delighted by your approval, my lady.~
@643  = ~As far as I'm concerned all it is going to bring me is a speedier demise. These unrelenting foes would kill the general much more swiftly than the small fry.~
@644  = ~I'll do whatever pleases me, Peony. Got it?~
@645  = ~So you like bossing folks around? Pish-tosh. I say, slow down, or your head will grow too big, and explode! Kaboom!~
@646  = ~I won't let that happen, I promise.~
@647  = ~I'll do my best to prevent this unfortunate occurrence, my lady, and I thank you for the warning.~
@648  = ~Tee-heee! (She does her best to imitate Nord's gruff voice.) 'The bloody pup needs free ranging to grow into a bloody wolf like his bloody sire.' I might have omitted a couple of bloodies, but that's the gist of it. Just don't let your head grow too big... young wolf!~
@649  = ~Well, as long as you don't let your head grow too big, it's all right.~
@650  = ~At least Nord seemed to think so, what with putting you in charge.~
@651  = ~I didn't ask for it, Peony.~
@652  = ~I know! It's great, isn't it?!~
@653  = ~He probably sought to sweeten my last days, the noble soul.~
@654  = ~I don't really know what he thought. ~
@655  = ~Peony, I let the old man go. I might have used gentler words, but the truth is I'm a born leader and I will act as such.~
@656  = ~At least Nord seems to think so, what with putting you in charge.~
@657  = ~I don't really know what he thinks. Why won't you ask him?~
@658  = ~I think I earned this position due to me being a born leader. And I will act as such.~
@659  = ~Hey, I told you how happy I was when I first saw you. Your turn!~
@660  = ~I thought: here stands another victim of corruption amongst the officials responsible for the docks' renovation.~
@661  = ~Nothing, my lady. For I was awestruck by your beauty and therefore couldn't think.~
@662  = ~That I was seeing the city of my birth for the last time, and what a pity that a maiden so young was so eager to join our hopeless cause. ~
@663  = ~To be honest, I don't remember. Everything was happening so fast for me....~
@664  = ~No, it isn't.~
@665  = ~I thought that you looked like a pest, and the first impression proved to be true.~
@666  = ~Surely that's not *all*. I mean... there's you!~
@667  = ~As if a pirate-gentleman is something unheard of. There *thousands* of songs about them. Helg the Fairhanded, and Veizen, and Dallion, and... thousands, I tell you, thousands!~
@668  = ~You already are. Just, well, stay the course.~
@669  = ~Oh, you look absolutely adorable with that bad boy look on your face!~
@670  = ~Well, it's got to count for something!~
@671  = ~No, no, please don't! It's a very sweet thought, really.~
@672  = ~Oh? I find that things brighten up when you smile instead of weeping generally. You should try it!~
@673  = ~You're just too plain self-centered. It's not good for your health, you know.~
@674  = ~As if talking to me is some kind of a torture. Here, take this, Lord Sourface! (Sticks her tongue out at you.)~
@675  = ~Wow, where did they teach you talk like that?! Are you a real gentleman?~
@676  = ~I suppose I am. If being a paladin's son counts.~
@677  = ~(With a crooked smile) More of a 'gentleman of fortune' nowadays.~
@678  = ~No, and I don't want to be.~
@679  = ~For you, Peony, I can be.~
@680  = ~Oh, dear gods. The other day you wanted me to be a pirate, now you want me to be a gentleman... is making up your mind too much to hope for?~
@681  = ~When men face death every minute of every day, some debase themselves, and others find the last retreat in keeping up with who they are. I'm one of the latter. My manners are all that I have left of my former life.~
@682  = ~That was really nice, gentlemen-like. Are you a real gentleman?~
@683  = ~Oh, dear gods. Another day you wanted me to be a pirate, now you want me to be a gentleman... is  making up your mind too much to hope for?~
@684  = ~Then don't, smarty-pants. Instead tell me what you remember thinking about me. You can do that, can't you? The very first thing?~
@685  = ~I remember nothing, my lady. For I was awestruck by your beauty and therefore couldn't think.~
@686  = ~I was wondering why you were smiling when you should have been weeping. ~
@687  = ~It crossed my mind, that maybe you and I... oh, what a completely hopeless thought, and how I regret telling you! ~
@688  = ~He-he-he! If only it was that simple. It's a spell! But at least you *noticed* my hair. I hoped people would, and it sort of worked! I'm a genius.~
@689  = ~My hair? You noticed my hair? Ye-e-e-s! I hoped it would work and it did! I'm a genius. ~
@690  = ~And what, what else do you remember thinking about me? The very first thing?~
@691  = ~It's surprising how often I get that! And all from people who came to love me to bits after. Yep.~
@692  = ~Oops.~
@693  = ~Oh. But later? When I did join in and we started traveling together, what was the first thing you remember thinking about me?~
@694  = ~And when I did join in? ~
@695  = ~That I was seeing the city of my birth for the last time.~
@696  = ~(Giggles.) Oh, this is sooo tacky, yet so pleasant anyway!~
@697  = ~ I should have foreseen that a scolding would come along with praise. For nothing sweet in our sorrowful world comes without more than a shade of bitterness. ~
@698  = ~Er...?~
@699  = ~Your hair, lady.~
@700  = ~Because they hire the worst scam instead of qualified painters, hence someone managed to drop a bucket of dye on you.~
@701  = ~He-he, I thought some prankster upended a bucket a paint over you while the watch looked another way!~
@702  = ~Does anything compare in its pointlessness to having to explain a joke? ~
@703  = ~Read my lips: I don't want to talk about it. ~
@704  = ~We're rookies on our first adventure... together!~
@705  = ~Yes, and due to this unfortunate synergy we are likely to die together quite soon.~
@706  = ~Wow, but you're a brute. Typical pirate.~
@707  = ~So they all say.~
@708  = ~Don't we all? But you seem to be in a hurry too!~
@709  = ~You're from Luskan.~
@710  = ~So? Not everyone from Luskan is a pirate.~
@711  = ~What can one do in the face of such impeccable logic but to give up? What difference does it make anyway, seeing how we're going to be dead shortly?~
@712  = ~My lady, I fear you are a victim of a common misconception.~
@713  = ~Yep, born and raised! But not a pirate.~
@714  = ~And you're that stupid, eh?~
@715  = ~(Claps her hands.) How very, very exciting! A real pirate from Luskan!~
@716  = ~The autho- What, here? In the war-torn Icewind Dale? He-he-he! Don't worry, you can be a pirate all you want! Isn't it phantasmagoric?~
@717  = ~Oh, wonderful. No, not wonderful. Phantasmagoric. I can be a pirate. (Roll your eyes.)~
@718  = ~You're right. The authorities won't have to bother, as there are plenty who'd enforce the 'good pirate is a dead pirate' policy. And they would care even less than you (if that's even possible!) to check that I'm actually a pirate.~
@719  = ~Peony, I'd like to die in peace.~
@720  = ~Very well, I'm a pirate. Perhaps this admission will stop *something* pointless. If only I could derive a better illusion of having a small measure of control over destiny from it.~
@721  = ~Anyhow, I meet you, and you're a phantasmagoricaly dashing pirate from Luskan!~
@722  = ~My lady, you're mistaken. I'm not a buccaneer, but indeed the eldest son and heir of Ser Roederic the Fierce.~
@723  = ~Lady? I like that! Though sort of stuffy. Ahem... I'll think about it later.~
@724  = ~And? Where were I? Aha!~
@725  = ~Nope! Not the smallest bit grisly. And you only cough phlegm when some bastard caves your chest in, but who doesn't?~
@726  = ~Hey, you aren't going to die, silly. I promise.~
@727  = ~Oh, pish-tosh!~
@728  = ~Seriously, I thought all adventurers were grisly old-timers coughing phlegm and telling the same tale fifteen times in a row! And here I meet you....~
@729  = ~(Clear your throat and spit under her feet.) Now, lass, didn't I tell you how I was thrown overboard and ripped out a shark's throat with only my nails?~
@730  = ~He-he, yeah, something like that.~
@731  = ~You're taking the words right out of my mouth!~
@732  = ~Hey, at least we'll do it in a good company!~
